Create a plan

**Background:** This project wraps pflag and cobra so that very little of these
libraries are visible or usable on the seam.

Currently users need to run `arg.AddFlag(cl, ...)` to add a new flag, or
`arg.Positional(...)` for a positonal, and `arg.Unmatched(cl, ...)` for unmatched.
Naming is misaligned, and this appears "C-like" instead of Go-like.

## Goal

Expand `CommandLine` to have `CommandLine.Add(args...Arg)`, where `Arg` is an
interace with an unexported func `register(cl *CommandLine)` for registering
itself to a command line object.

It is implemented by `Positional`, `Unmatched`, and `Flag`.

To do this:

* We will need to expose `arg.PositionalArg` and `arg.UnmatchedArg`, and have it
  implemented the sealed `Arg` interface. This can just be a thin wrapper around
  the `argreg.*` types of the same name. They don't need to expose any visible
  API to the user.

* We will rename `arg.Flag` to `arg.FlagArg` (just a rename) and have it implement
  the sealed interface [1]

[1]: Note that `pflag.FlagSet.VarP` is just a shorthand for:

    ```go
    func (f *FlagSet) VarPF(value Value, name, shorthand, usage string) *Flag {
      // Remember the default value as a string; it won't change.
      flag := &Flag{
        Name:      name,
        Shorthand: shorthand,
        Usage:     usage,
        Value:     value,
        DefValue:  value.String(),
      }
      f.AddFlag(flag)
      return flag
    }
    ```

    So a refactoring here is simple: just `VarP` with a flag construction inline,
    and make `register(cl *CommandLine)` do the `f.AddFlag(...)` for the flag.

Rename `arg.AddFlag` to just `arg.Flag`

Update any documentation to ensure it's referring to the proper names, since
some of the `docs/` and tutorials will be out of date now. If you find any
old references to a `flag` package, ensure that is updated as well.

Additionally: Add helpers for:

* `CommandLine.AddFlagSet(fs *pflag.FlagSet)` that adds all flags from `fs` into `CommandLine`.

